252 (c)(1) Each Every public school in this state shall prepare and annually review and
253 update as necessary a school safety plan to help curb the growing incidence of violence
254 in schools, to respond effectively to such incidents, and to provide a safe learning
255 environment for Georgia's children, teachers, and other school personnel. Such plan shall
256 also address preparedness for natural disasters, hazardous materials or radiological
257 accidents, acts of violence, and acts of terrorism. School safety plans of public schools
258 shall be prepared with input from students enrolled in that school, parents or legal
259 guardians of such students, teachers in that school, community leaders, other school
260 employees and school district employees, and local law enforcement, juvenile court, fire
261 service, public safety, and emergency management agencies. As part of such plans,
262 public schools shall provide for the coordination with local law enforcement agencies and
263 the local juvenile court system. Such plans of public schools shall be submitted to the
264 local law enforcement agency designated as having approval authority by the local board
265 of education.
266 (2) School safety plans shall include, at a minimum, the following strategy areas:
267 (1)(A) Training school administrators, teachers, and support staff, including, but not
268 limited to, school resource officers, security officers, secretaries, custodians, and bus
269 drivers, on school violence prevention, school security, school threat assessment,
270 mental health awareness, and school emergency planning best practices;
271 (2)(B) Evaluating and refining school security measures;
272 (3)(C) Updating and exercising school emergency preparedness plans;
273 (4)(D) Strengthening partnerships with public safety officials; and
274 (5)(E) Creating enhanced crisis communications plans and social media strategies;
275 (F) Addressing security issues in school safety zones, as defined in Code
276 Section 16-11-127.1;
277 (G) Addressing security issues involving school functions held during noninstructional
278 hours; and
